hi @victoris93 thanks for the bug report - does this issue come up when importing from other modules? 

@daxpryce the other day you said there was some issue with llvmlite you had seen before with people's installs, is this that same issue?
@bdpedigo yes, it throws an identical error when I try to import other modules.

Is there a reason you are trying to use graspy 0.3.0 instead of the most recent version of graspologic? I just noticed that. 

Though, ultimately I think this has something to do with how numba and/or llvmlite are installed on your machine. Could you provide the output of either `pip list` or `conda list` for the current python environment you are using?

@bdpedigo I was just following the tutorial which used graspy specifically. Would switching to graspology make a difference?

> @bdpedigo I was just following the tutorial which used graspy specifically. Would switching to graspology make a difference?

We are no longer supporting/maintaining graspy (the name more or less just changed to graspologic), most things should still work if you just change graspy -> graspologic. Which tutorial are you trying to follow? 

Again, not sure that this is causing this particular issue though. One thing I could suggest is creating a new conda environment and specifying a few dependencies: 

`conda create -n <new env> numba llvmlite scikit-learn scipy numpy`

after that you can `pip install graspologic` and see if it works. 

though @daxpryce I think has seen an issue similar to this so he may have better ideas!

@bdpedigo after I've tried to create a new environment:
```
CondaVerificationError: The package for libllvm10 located at /Users/VictoriaShevchenko/opt/anaconda3/pkgs/libllvm10-10.0.1-h76017ad_5
appears to be corrupted. The path 'lib/libLLVM-10.dylib'
specified in the package manifest cannot be found.

  packages: defaults/osx-64::intel-openmp-2021.2.0-hecd8cb5_564, defaults/osx-64::llvm-openmp-10.0.0-h28b9765_0
  path: 'lib/libiomp5.dylib'
``` 
Any ideas? 😅  llvmlite seems to be the problem

does 
`conda create -n <new env> numba llvmlite`
work (without any scipy/sklearn/etc) ? 

Could also try 

`conda config --add channels conda-forge`
`conda config --set channel_priority strict`

and retry steps above but this would set your default channels to conda-forge https://conda-forge.org/index.html instead of the anaconda defaults
@victoris93 just wondering if any of that helped?

@bdpedigo actually today I had to reinstall mvlearn since previous manipulations had somehow affected its dependency on graspy. So I decided to stick to the visualization functions provided by mvlearn. Once I removed it and installed it again with pip3, it went back to normal. Thanks for your help though! It's just for now I really need mvlearn to work 😅

Thanks for letting us know @victoris93!

In general, trying to troubleshoot a global(ish) environment is super challenging.  For issues like this, we really would like to ask you to:
- create a new virtual environment or conda equivalent
- Install only graspologic
- Replicate that you cannot import graspologic (or, specifically, the import statement that blew up catastrophically in your older environment)

That's a good starting point for us as we start our search.  If it's doing it in the fresh environment, and it's a python+os+platform configuration we support, then that is 100% on us (even if it's a dependency of ours, we still have a responsibility to find a work around or replace the library, which... is not awesome, but we can't let downstream deps make us stop working in a fresh install!)  

If it's _not_ doing it in the fresh environment, then it gives us a place where we can compare the deltas in `pip list` (or conda equivalent (???? I don't use conda so... my nomenclature is probably off)) between the two environments so we try to hypothesize some reasons for why it's not working for you and try to work through them.

I'm going to mark this as closed **for the moment**, but if you get to a point where you want to try to dig into this some more, feel free to reopen this ticket, or open a new one and reference this one so we can try to pull together all the information you've already provided.
